Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Halve @grape tomatoes{4%oz} lengthwise. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2%unit}, separating whites from greens. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.

Pat @shrimp{10%oz} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with half the @Italian seasoning{1%tbsp} (you'll use the rest later), @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add shrimp and cook, stirring occasionally, until opaque and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%oz} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes} (you'll start the tomatoes after 5 minutes).

Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

Once spaghetti has cooked 5 minutes, melt @butter{2%tbsp} in pan used for shrimp over medium-high heat.

Add tomatoes, scallion whites, and garlic; cook, until scallions and garlic are softened and fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: If mixture begins to brown too quickly, reduce heat to medium.

Reduce heat under pan with tomato mixture to medium. Stir in @cream sauce base{4%oz}, @cream cheese{2%tbsp}, and remaining Italian seasoning. Bring to a simmer; cook until melted and combined. Season with salt and pepper.

Add shrimp and drained spaghetti to pan with sauce; toss until coated and creamy, adding splashes of reserved pasta cooking water as needed. Stir in half the @Parmesan cheese{3%tbsp} and season with salt and pepper.

Divide shrimp spaghetti between #bowls{}. Sprinkle with scallion greens and remaining Parmesan. Serve.

> Our chefs have dreamed up the pasta equivalent of an Italian serenade, and it hits all the right notes. Now that's amore!